1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Qe2 {[pgndiagram] The
so-called Worall attack. White defends the e-pawn with his queen, frees the d1
square for his rook and plans Rd1-c3-d4.  The main drawback of the move is
that the Queen is slightly exposed on this square, and Bg4 move is always
slightly annoying for White} b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a4 {[pgndiagram] But this is very
rare move, even from today's perspective} (8. c3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Rd1 O-O 11.
d3 {[pgndiagram] Constitutes the main line nowadays, with slower play, more
characteristic of the d3 Anti Berlin lines}) 8... Bg4 {This is not a pawn
sacrifice; Black is threatening Nd4} 9. c3 (9. axb5 Nd4 {Is really unpleasant})
9... O-O {[pgndiagram] But this time this really is a pawn sacrifice.. Or more
precisely a pseudo-sacrifice} 10. axb5 {Accepting the gauntlet. With hindsight,
it might have been wiser to refrain from doing it} (10. h3 {Or}) (10. d3) 10...
axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Qxb5 Na7 $1 {[pgndiagram] A key move that I imagine
Fine missed} 13. Qe2 (13. Qa6 Nxe4 {[pgndiagram] Is no good for White as well})
13... Qxe4 14. Qxe4 Nxe4 {[pgndiagram] Now Black has a very pleasant endgame.
He will take on f3 and spoil White's structure. This factor is more important
than the two bishops here} 15. d4 (15. Bd1 {Trying to defend against Bxf3 is
too artificial for instance} Nc5 {The knight jump to d3 is really unpleasant}
16. d4 Nd3 17. Be2 Nxc1 18. Rxc1 e4 {[pgndiagram] And White loses a piece})
15... Bxf3 16. gxf3 Ng5 17. Kg2 Rb8 18. Bc4 exd4 19. cxd4 Ne6 20. d5 {
[pgndiagram] This pawn severely restricts White's bishop} (20. Bxe6 fxe6 21.
Nc3 d5 {Is also not very wise. Black's pieces are too active, White's pawns
are all weak (3 islands)}) 20... Nc5 21. Nc3 Nc8 22. Re1 Kf8 23. Re2 f5 {
[pgndiagram]Not the most precise} (23... Rb4 24. Ba2 Nd3 {[pgndiagram]Would
have won the b-pawn}) 24. Nb5 Nb6 25. b3 Nxd5 26. Nd4 Nb4 27. Bd2 $2 {
[pgndiagram]A mistake} (27. Nxf5 {There was nothing wrong with taking the
f-pawn, emphasizing the drawback of it's early advance}) 27... d5 28. Bxb4 Rxb4
29. Nc6 dxc4 30. Nxb4 cxb3 {[pgndiagram] Fine possibly evaluated this endgame
wrongly. It is probably close to lost for White} 31. Nd5 Nd3 $1 {Keres plays
this phase of the game brilliantly, making use of every possible tactical idea
there is} 32. Rd2 {Obviously, White can't take the bishop} (32. Rxe7 b2) (32.
Nxe7 Nf4+) 32... b2 $1 33. Rd1 c5 $6 (33... Nc1 {WAs even easier} 34. Nc3 Bf6
35. Nb1 c5 {[pgndiagram] And White is paralyzed}) 34. Kf1 c4 {Here again, Nc1
came into consideration} 35. Rb1 Bc5 36. Ke2 Bxf2 37. Ne3 c3 {[pgndiagram]
Another very strong tactical solution and the only way to win} 38. Nc2 (38.
Kxd3 Bxe3 39. Kxc3 Bc1 {[pgndiagram] Is basically a pawn endgame in which
Black is winning}) 38... Ne1 $1 {Those escapades by Black's minor pieces
though..} 39. Na3 (39. Nxe1 Bxe1 40. Kxe1 c2 {[pgndiagram] Is too obvious...
at least from the comfort of my own home with the engine running and enjoying
Black's position}) 39... Bc5 $6 {[pgndiagram] Slightly careless} (39... Bh4 {
